The paper deals with graph compression and indexing, which are core topics in computer science. The use of recursive graph bisection is a common technique in graph partitioning and is closely related to data structures and algorithms. Therefore, cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) is the most likely category. The paper also discusses the use of graph reordering for assigning document identifiers in inverted indexes, which falls under the scope of cs.IR (Information Retrieval). The paper's focus on locality and compression makes it relevant to cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) and cs.DB (Databases). Finally, the use of parallel and distributed implementations suggests a connection to cs.CC (Computational Complexity).
